New Hope for India
Cambridge, USA — India's latest elections may be the most significant positive economic event since 2014.
Indian voters decisively rejected the Congress Party, which has almost always ruled India since its independence from British rule in 1947.
They might feel happy about this decision.
Sonia Gandhi, the widow of Rajiv Gandhi, the former prime minister and leader of the Congress Party, has been acting as the de facto leader since 1998, while Prime Minister Singh has been little more than a figurehead.
Under her leadership, the Congress Party pursued populist agendas and increased transfer payments, leading to India's annual GDP growth rate falling below 4% in 2013.
Per capita GDP remains around $4,000, less than half of China's.
The newly elected prime minister, Narendra Modi, promised during his campaign to bring rapid growth in employment and income across India, just as he did when he was chief minister of Gujarat.
Under Modi's leadership, Gujarat has become a business-friendly state, expanding economic activities and attracting commercial investments from both within and outside India.
An important feature of the latest election is that the BJP, led by Modi, secured an absolute majority in the Lok Sabha, which is arguably an unprecedented achievement in India.
Therefore, Modi does not need to compromise with other national or regional parties to pursue his legislative agenda.
Two key officials will assist Modi in the economic plan.
New Finance Minister Arun Jaitley has extensive political experience, having served as a minister in the previous BJP government.
Jeter is also renowned as a strategic thinker known for his compassionate approach to commercial interests.
Raghuram Rajan will continue to serve as the Governor of the Reserve Bank of India (RBI). Rajan is an outstanding economist, and during his tenure as RBI Governor, he demonstrated a strong desire to reduce India's high double-digit annual inflation rate and attempted to reform some of the inherent productivity constraints within India's financial sector.
The measures needed to stimulate economic growth will take time to be implemented and to yield results.
But if you want to know whether the new government is taking action to achieve faster long-term growth, you should examine whether progress has been made in the following ten policy areas.
Education.
Although India has excellent higher education and technical institutions, only a small portion of the population can access the opportunities they offer, because primary and secondary education in India is severely underdeveloped.
Only 60% of adult Indians have literacy skills equivalent to a primary school level.
The teachers themselves have poor educational backgrounds and lack motivation for their work; many of them hardly ever appear at their schools.
Infrastructure.
India needs better roads and ports to efficiently transport goods across the country and around the world.
The recent expansion of private air routes and airports indicates that private enterprises can also play a role in this field.
Financial integration.
Large budget deficits absorb national savings that could otherwise be used to expand business investment. Budget deficits lead to an increase in national debt that can only be financed through future taxes.
Privatization.
The manufacturing and other industrial enterprises under the Indian government operate inefficiently, often resulting in the consumption of national savings.
Selling these enterprises directly helps accelerate economic growth.
Cancel subsidies.
Subsidies for electricity and energy lead to wasteful overconsumption and increased fiscal deficits.
Although these subsidies are politically difficult to abolish, they should be replaced with cash transfers. Currently, India's cash transfer efficiency is relatively high due to the remarkable new fingerprint-based cash transfer system.
Agricultural Reform.
Under the current system, the government purchases, stores, and distributes agricultural products.
The result was that a large amount of goods were stockpiled in warehouses, while production incentives were misdirected.
The agricultural market should be privatized.
Property rights and regional division.
As long as you have been to Mumbai or other large Indian cities, you will see that zoning restrictions cause poor land use in urban areas, which constrains the initial dilution.
Unclear property rights, especially those concerning farmland, have hindered industrialization in rural areas.
Relax restrictions on foreign investment.
Currently, foreign enterprises cannot become the controlling shareholders of banks and insurance companies.
Relaxing these restrictions can strengthen the financial sector and play an important role in economic growth.
Tax reform.
India's complex federal and state sales tax system distorts domestic trade.
The debate over replacing these taxes with a national value-added tax and implementing a divided tax system has been ongoing for a long time, and it should now enter the implementation phase.
Corruption.
The high-level corruption cases have undermined economic confidence and hindered officials' decision-making.
India is also deeply affected by petty corruption, and bribery has become a common feature in all business and personal transactions.
The government should severely punish high-level corruption and curb small-scale corruption by implementing a new cash transfer payment system.
Driven by stronger growth and expectations of increased profits, India's stock market has already risen by 20% this year.
Now, Modi and the BJP need to prove to the world that they can fulfill their campaign promises.
